A timeline replayed once yields one timing, which carries no account of its own reliability, so a run read against a run reports the machine's drift as often as the code.

`--perf-replay` now takes `repeats=N` and reports the spread alongside the smallest difference the timeline can resolve, marking a timeline NOISY when its spread swamps the effects worth hunting. The new `--perf-compare` pairs runs acquired alternately in one session, so the drift both versions share cancels, and returns INCONCLUSIVE when the confidence interval straddles zero.
